column360: I tried different methods  such as going majority asset A or majority asset B during some paths. I went with gut feelings sometimes  or if there were multiple low numbers in a row  I invested more in A because I felt the next number had a higher probability of being high  even though the chances were random. I understood everything  but I wish I had more experience or knowledge in investing to learn how to maximize profits  even though the return rate on Asset A was quite random.

I encountered a few problems when doing this experiment.  | A few times (during 9 paths in total) I was unable to allocate my assets  as the bar would remain grey without showing any indication of being clicked on. I tried clicking on every part of the bar  yet it did not help. Thus some of my answers will be scewed and not reflect accurate assessements on my part.  | It was not only one bar per path  I should note  but this problem would occur repeatedly - up to 6 times within a single path.  |  | Otherwise  this experiment showed me that I have to do some research in the investment sector before actually going ahead and investing in a stockmarket that is not always predictable.

I wasn't in any way sure of my investment decisions. Essentially  I raised my investment in Asset A after a negative return and lowered it after a higher return. I think I understood most of the experiment well.

In the first period  I tried to distribute my investment more or less equally between the two assets. Then In Part I of the experiment  I tried to risk and put more of my investment in asset A. Sometimes  it yielded a great return (over $20)  but most of the time  it gave me a return right around my original amount ($3). As I started doing the Part II of the experiment  I went safe and put more of my money in asset B because it was constant. though my return was not that great  I made sure that it was greater than my initial amount of $3. When I was able to check how other participants do in Part III  I thought I was more on the "high return" side as I recorded the highest amount a few times. That made me feel good and keep the same strategy as I was using in Part II.
I invested mostly in Asset A. Whenever I had above five dollars  I would buy the four percent chance for twenty dollars. The amount I get depended mostly on the high multipliers from Asset A.

I understood the experiment well. In general  it was fun to do it. Of course  I was happier when I earned some money and it felt that I made a right investment decision even though I did not really have a control over that. When I lost I felt I am making bad choices only. When my earnings were really low  most of the time  I was taking 100% risk of investing in assest A. I knew that there is only 4% chance to win $20 but I hoped to win it every time I spent $1 on it; I won once;/ and I could expect that. Also  I felt that it was "easier" to get more return in the first part than it was in second and thrid. In other words  I felt that more often the return was higher in first part of the experiment rather than in secod or third part.

I usually started out investing 50% of my money in each A and B. If I lost money from A  I would distribute a smaller percentage to it. However  if I had lost money from investing in A for many periods  then I would increase my percent invested in A because a coefficient greater than 1.03 should be coming up soon. Also  even if the coefficient was less than 1.03  I couldn't lose a large amount of money because I had so little.  |  | Thus  when I had a low amount of money  I became more risky and invested more in A. when I had a relatively large amount of money  I invested a smaller percentage in A because I knew B would yield a coefficient of 1.03  and losing 50% of my investment in A  if I had a large amount of money  would take a significant chunk out of my total amount of money.
Really boring experiment. Not much to do except move a line up and down. Investing isn't the same if it is not your own money  even if it is what we earn at the end  it's still money in our pocket.
I didn't make my investments in a consistent way.  If my investments reached a higher amount then I would invest more in Asset B in order to maintain the higher dollar amount.
